{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475520"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:33:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:33:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.16,0.04,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52092"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5142"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"768"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49585"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52092"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a left ankle injury sustained during a basketball game. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is localised swelling of the left ankle without bruising. Palpation of the left medial malleolus elicits severe tenderness. The range of movement of the left ankle is limited by pain in both passive and active movement. Neurological examination of the lower limbs is normal. Both posterior tibialis and dorsalis pedis pulses are present and strong bilaterally. X-rays reveal a Salter-Harris IV fracture of the distal tibia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is this patient most likely to develop?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Limb-length discrepancy","Superficial peroneal nerve injury","Osteomyelitis","Re-fracture","Dorsalis pedis artery injury"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained a Salter-Harris Type IV fracture of the distal tibia. When counselling the patient and his parents about potential complications, the most important one to discuss is \u003Cstrong\u003Elimb-length discrepancy\u003C/strong\u003E. The distal tibial physis is responsible for significant growth and leg lengthening until physeal closure, which typically occurs between ages 12-17 in females and 15-20 in males. Salter-Harris fractures, particularly Type IV, can cause premature closure of the physis, halting growth at the growth plate and potentially leading to persistent limb-length discrepancy. The risk of growth arrest is increased in this case due to the young age of the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperficial peroneal nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case. This nerve runs along the lateral aspect of the leg and ankle, and is more commonly injured in lateral ankle or distal fibular fractures. The patient\u0027s fracture involves the medial malleolus, and there are no neurological findings suggestive of superficial peroneal nerve injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammation of bone, usually due to infection. While it can occur as a complication of fractures, it is more common in open fractures or after open surgical procedures. There is no mention of an open wound in this case, making osteomyelitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERe-fracture\u003C/strong\u003E at the same location is a possible complication of some paediatric fractures, particularly greenstick fractures of long bones. However, it is relatively uncommon in Salter-Harris fractures of the ankle. The risk of re-fracture would be mitigated by appropriate initial management and follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsalis pedis artery injury\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication in ankle fractures. The dorsalis pedis artery is a continuation of the anterior tibial artery and runs along the dorsum of the foot. It is more likely to be injured in severe ankle fractures with significant displacement or open injuries. In this case, the dorsalis pedis pulse was noted to be present and strong, indicating that the artery is intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing Salter-Harris fractures, it\u0027s important to remember the classification system:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EType I: Fracture through the physis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EType II: Fracture through the physis and metaphysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EType III: Fracture through the physis and epiphysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EType IV: Fracture through the metaphysis, physis, and epiphysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EType V: Crush injury to the physis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType IV fractures, as seen in this case, have a higher risk of growth disturbances due to the involvement of all three components of the growing bone. Close follow-up and monitoring for limb-length discrepancy is crucial in the long-term management of these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ankle fractures in children can be associated with limb-length discrepancies.","Salter-Harris Type IV fractures of the distal tibia have a high risk of growth arrest, especially in younger children.","Counselling patients and parents about potential complications is an important part of fracture management in children."],"references":["Cepela DJ, Tartaglione JP, Dooley TP, Patel PN. Classifications in brief: Salter-Harris classification of pediatric physeal fractures. Clinical Orthopaedics and Related Research\u00ae. 2016 Nov;474:2531-7.","Kay RM, Matthys GA. Pediatric ankle fractures: evaluation and treatment. JAAOS-Journal of the American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons. 2001 Jul 1;9(4):268-78."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T13:11:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T13:12:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5142"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52092"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attribut